@MrYoda Here is an example of how to do that (if I understand problem correctly):
```python
import marshmallow as m
import marshmallow.fields as mf
from marshmallow.compat import with_metaclass
from collections import namedtuple, OrderedDict

LANGUAGES = ['en', 'de', 'fr']

class I18NMeta(type):
    def __new__(cls, name, bases, attrs):
        new_attrs = OrderedDict(attrs)
        if 'Meta' in attrs:
            for name in getattr(attrs['Meta'], 'i18n_fields', []):
                if name not in attrs:
                    continue

                field = attrs[name]
                for lang in LANGUAGES:
                    new_attrs['%s_%s' % (name, lang)] = field

        return type(name, bases, new_attrs)

class ModelSchema(with_metaclass(I18NMeta, m.Schema)):
    class Meta:
        ordered = True
        i18n_fields = ['value']

    value = mf.String()

Model = namedtuple('Model', ['value', 'value_en', 'value_de', 'value_fr'])

print ModelSchema().dump(Model('Hello', 'Hello', 'Hallo', 'Bonjour'))
# => MarshalResult(data=OrderedDict([(u'value', u'Hello'), (u'value_en', u'Hello'), (u'value_de', u'Hallo'), (u'value_fr', u'Bonjour')]), errors={})
```
Alternatively, you can use special type to mark localized strings:
```python
import marshmallow as m
import marshmallow.fields as mf
from marshmallow.compat import with_metaclass, iteritems
from collections import namedtuple, OrderedDict

LANGUAGES = ['en', 'de', 'fr']

class LocalizedString(mf.String):
    pass

class I18NMeta(type):
    def __new__(cls, name, bases, attrs):
        new_attrs = OrderedDict(attrs)
        for field_name, field in iteritems(attrs):
            if not isinstance(field, LocalizedString):
                continue

            for lang in LANGUAGES:
                new_attrs['%s_%s' % (field_name, lang)] = field

        return type(name, bases, new_attrs)

class ModelSchema(with_metaclass(I18NMeta, m.Schema)):
    value = LocalizedString()

Model = namedtuple('Model', ['value', 'value_en', 'value_de', 'value_fr'])

print ModelSchema().dump(Model('Hello', 'Hello', 'Hallo', 'Bonjour'))
```

@rhelmot Thanks for taking a look at this. Setting the SONAME correctly indeed is desirable.

> All this, of course, operates under the assumption that z3 only breaks its APIs on major version increments. If this is not the case we can change the soname to major.minor.

I don't know what the API stability policy is but if I take a look at the current version reported in `master` of `4.4.2.1` as the next version number then your assumption of breaking the API major version increments is wrong. I know because I [had to work around this in KLEE](https://github.com/klee/klee/commit/5960bc6387df8ec89e3e98ae3867b0a3c025033b). Specifically the interface of `Z3_get_error_msg()` changed between 4.4.1 and what is in the `master` branch.

If `4.4.2.1` is the next version of Z3 then `SONAME` will need to be `${Z3_VERSION_MAJOR}.${Z3_VERSION_MINOR}.${Z3_VERSION_PATCH}`

@wintersteiger @NikolajBjorner What will be the version number of the next release of Z3? I think it would be useful if it was `4.5.0.0` rather than `4.4.2.1` because then we could make it the policy that Z3's API may change if the the major or minor version gets bumped (i.e. there will be no API changes if the patch or tweak version get bumped). This would allow us to set the SONAME to `${Z3_VERSION_MAJOR}.${Z3_VERSION_MINOR}`

Is there a policy on API changes? If we were to follow [semantic versioning](http://semver.org/) then we would actually bump the major version every time we made an incompatible API change. I'm not sure if that's what we want but there needs to be some sort of policy so clients of Z3 can expect API breakages.

